description.narrative: The Somalia Joint Response is a project funded by the Dutch Ministry of Foreign Affairs through the Dutch Relief Alliance. The Consortium consists of four INGOs and six LNGOs and is led by Oxfam Novib. The four INGOs are: Oxfam Novib, Red een Kind, WorldVision and SOS Children#s Villages. The six LNGOs are: TASCO, Havoyoco, Candlelight, ZamZam, Dawa, KAALO. The Somalia Joint Response is present in Somaliland, Puntland and South Central (Mogadishu, Banadir). The proposed project aims to address the HRP objectives of providing life-saving and life-sustaining integrated, multi-sectoral assistance to reduce acute humanitarian need for communities affectedby the drought and protracted conflict. The Somalia Joint Response 2020 is a continuation of the response in 2019, and will focus on the following sectors: FSL, Protection, WASH, Health and Nutrition. A special focus will be on localisation and supporting LNGOs in capacity strengthening and becoming the lead of future responses. Improved accountability to affected populations will underpin the work of the response. The response will also subgrant the Somalia NGO Consortium for activities around localisation, risk management and coordination.

participating-org.narrative: Candle Light for Health and Education (CLHE) works in the Toghdeer region of Somalia and was founded in 1995. Its mandate is to contribute to setting up sustainable structures in education and healthcare. Its most important target group consists of women and other marginalised groups, such as returning refugees. CHLE is also working with former militia members and tries to integrate them in society. CLHE works closely with the local authorities, leaders and others. Its work includes formal and informaleducation, training,preventive healthcare, rehabilitating small school buildings, and small-scale income generating activities. CLHE also works on the environment. It is of the opinion that deforestation has a negative impact on cattle, which has negative consequences for people's health and nutrition. Not enough good grazing land and a lack of water increase people's mobility, disrupting education programs. Therelationship between Oxfam Novib and CLHE began in 1996. CLHE's organisation capacities havesince improved.
